<br>
As others have stated, the only reasonable way for a pet to hold agro is if no players are in mellee range of the mob. Most monks and SK's would get bored or frustrated not being able to actually mellee the mobs you fight, however. <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=azzabarr@themagicianstower>Azzabarr</A> at: 1/29/03 5:43:54 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#dcdeed><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub102.ezboard.com/bthemagicianstower.showUserPublicProfile?gid=jarlo99>Jarlo99</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Magician</span><br>  Posts: 12<br> <font color=#333333>(1/29/03 5:46:57 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub102.ezboard.com/fthemagicianstowerfrm29.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=974.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: .</span><hr size=1> I dont think you need to use earth pet for this. All of them hold aggro from caster types pretty easily unless they overburn.<br>
<br>
You can make earth pet hold aggro if you drag the mob RIGHT ON TOP of the pet before it attacks.  When things are rooted they attack the closest thing and ignore the hate list, thus they will thump on the pet-- I havent tested this in a while so may have changed but I know it worked well in the past.  May test it in a few days though.<br>
